def show_max (a, b, *more, **fields)
  print(a, b, more, fields)
show_max(1 , 2 ,3 ,4 ,5 ,6 , name="Dave", height=184)

"""
A parameter with * before it wraps the arguments given to it into a tupple. 
the condition is that the arguments must be positional argumets and not keyword arguments.
in the example above: 3, 4, 5 and 6 will be wrapped into a tupple and go into the variable "more". (because 1 is a and 2 is b)

A parameter with ** before it wraps the arguments given to it into a dictionary.
the arguments must be keyword arguments.
this means that a parameter with ** (double star) before it, must be in the end because keyword arguments must not be followed by positional arguments.
